<br>
As Rep. Markey said, back in 1998 when the first tritium tests were proposed:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> LET'S KEEP &quot;ATOMS FOR PEACE&quot; <br>
AND &quot;ATOMS FOR WAR&quot; SEPARATE <br>
by Representative Edward J. Markey (D-MA ) <br>
June 8, 1998 <br>
<br>
Last week's disturbing news that Pakistan has joined India testing nuclear explosives poses dramatic new challenges for U.S. nuclear non-proliferation policy. Not only will America need to take effective measures to convince both nation's to step back from their nuclear brinksmanship, but it also will need to redouble its efforts to convince other potential nuclear weapons states to forgo testing and deploying nuclear arsenals. <br>
<br>
Since the dawn of the nuclear age, the United States has recognized the need to maintain a separation between its military nuclear program ( &quot;Atoms for War&quot; )   and its civilian nuclear energy program ( &quot;Atoms for Peace&quot; )  . Congress codified this long-respected practice in 1982 when it explicitly barred the use of civilian nuclear power plants to fabricate fissile materials for nuclear explosives. <br>
<br>
Preserving our credibility to press for the strongest possible global nonproliferation regime isn't the only reason to keep the two nuclear genies in separate bottles. If we mix the production of bomb-making material with the production of civilian electricity, the most mundane individual daily tasks take on new meaning. The mere act of popping toast could become a profound event. <br>
<br>
But by far the most important reason to shun the cogeneration of megawatts and megatons is to maintain our leadership role in pressing nuclear threshold states to refrain from using their civilian nuclear facilities to produce weapons-grade materials. Our moral authority will collapse if we use our civilian nuclear power plants for the very same military purposes we proselytize against abroad. <br>
<br>
The 1982 law, known as the Hart-Simpson-Mitchell amendment to the Atomic Energy Act, prevents civilian nuclear power plants from being used to produce plutonium or highly-enriched uranium for nuclear explosives. Unfortunately, there is a loophole: it does not cover tritium, a radioactive gas used to boost the yield of nuclear explosives. <br>
<br>
Currently, the Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA ) is trying to exploit this loophole by offering to contract with the Department of Energy to produce tritium in the uncompleted Bellefonte nuclear power reactor in Alabama. If DOE were to accept this proposal for a federal bailout of a nuclear reactor in the Tennessee Valley, the U.S. would lose all claim to the nuclear nonproliferation high ground around the globe. How could we argue with a straight face to nuclear threshold states that they should refrain from using their civilian nuclear programs for military purposes, when we were violating this principle here at home? <br>
<br>
Fortunately, just a few weeks ago, the House passed an amendment offered by Representative Lindsey Graham (R-SC ) and myself to close this loophole in U.S. nuclear nonproliferation law. The Markey-Graham amendment would make tritium subject to the same nonproliferation restrictions as other nuclear weapons materials. <br>
<br>
Under our amendment, DOE would still be free to pursue other viable options to meet any future national security needs for this material. If there is a national security need for tritium, this gas would have to be produced in a special purpose DOE facility. DOE already has been studying such options, and some experts believe that producing tritium in a DOE-owned linear accelerator could actually cost less than the Bellefonte bailout. However, under the Markey-Graham amendment, DOE would still retain the option of authorizing production of special nuclear material in a civilian facility in the event Congress has declared a state of war or national emergency. In this manner, we can assure that any action to breach the separation between the military and civilian nuclear programs only occurs in a genuine emergency and as a last resort. <br>
<br>
In the aftermath of the Indian and Pakistani nuclear explosions and the prospect of a full-scale nuclear arms race in South Asia, the Markey-Graham amendment ensures that as a weapons-state, the U.S. remains in the strongest possible position to argue to non-weapons states not to use their civilian nuclear energy programs for military purposes. <br>
<br>
